                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d669">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.20/474½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by President <persName type="from"
                            >Roosevelt</persName> to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-07-26">July 26,
                            1939</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I do not agree with this estimate of the situation.<note n="40" xml:id="d669fn40"
                        >See <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> There is, of course, always danger
                    of some internal trouble in Liberia but the fact of possessing even two or three
                    line mobile field pieces is going to keep a raiding enemy cruiser or submarine
                    out of the roadstead. The cost can be made negligible by cutting red tape.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>F[<hi rend="smallcaps">ranklin</hi>] D. R[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >oosevelt</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
